Imagine a long web page with many sections (such as a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific section (e.g., page.html#section7), can the web server send that section first and then the rest of the content?
Stream order:
1. The beginning of the HTML document up to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for the 7th section
3. The HTML code for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser must ensure that parts 1 to 6 are inserted above part 7 on the web page.
Is this reasonable? Will it be useful?
My goal is to have the linked section (#section7) render as quickly as possible without having to re-implement it using JavaScript or similar technologies. I want a very long HTML document, but the linked section should still render quickly. This can be achieved simply with HTML.
Content can be streamed in this way, and the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 It is actually possible to reorder the document content without using JavaScript. However, if you want the server to do something, you cannot use the URL hash part, but instead use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to view first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Using CSS
2. Using templates with slots
@user23 Yes. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) and the DOM order are inconsistent. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, and the browser could arrange the content in order into the DOM, that might be useful.
However, the slot method seems promising. I'll try it.
@user22 Oh, are you trying to have the browser automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's exactly what I'm thinking. The only reason for transmitting section 7 first is to allow the user to see it as quickly as possible. If this can be achieved without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, so the browser can ensure that the final DOM order and visual order are consistent.
In other words, transmit section 7 first, but the final result (DOM and visual appearance) should be exactly the same as if all sections were transmitted in order.
@user22 @user33 You can check out PHOOOS without using JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
